{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17605013","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17605013"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:02:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:02:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15860"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15860","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15860"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.81,0.12,0,0.08,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8551"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71523"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8551","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8551"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15860"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57032"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"8605"},{"type":"tags","id":"10160"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20511"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20515"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71523","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71523"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring early embryological development, the embryonic disc differentiates into three primary germ layers: ectoderm, mesoderm, and endoderm.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures is derived from embryonic ectoderm?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Melanocytes","Smooth muscle","Cardiac muscle","Blood vessels","Bone marrow"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EEmbryonic ectoderm gives rise to multiple structures throughout the body. Important ectodermal derivatives include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESurface ectoderm: epidermis, hair, nails, lens of the eye\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENeural tube: brain, spinal cord, posterior pituitary\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENeural crest: \u003Cstrong\u003Emelanocytes,\u003C/strong\u003E peripheral nerves, ganglia, chromaffin cells\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMelanocytes are neural crest derivatives that migrate extensively throughout the body, making this the correct answer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESmooth muscle\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Ecardiac muscle\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Eblood vessels\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003Ebone marrow\u003C/strong\u003E are all derived from mesoderm.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The embryo develops three primary germ layers: ectoderm, mesoderm, and endoderm.","The ectoderm differentiates into the epidermis, neural tissue, and neural crest derivatives.","Neural crest cells migrate extensively to form diverse structures including melanocytes and peripheral nerves."],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015.","Shakhova O, Sommer L. Neural crest-derived stem cells. 2010 May 4. In: StemBook [Internet]. Cambridge (MA): Harvard Stem Cell Institute; 2008. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK44752/# doi: 10.3824/stembook.1.51.1"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57032"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15860"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57032","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57032"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-19T04:37:00+